{"author":{"id":"2fec99dc79e1c05dcc8e6b4c2ef3b9c29fe62a9801fe4df49021516fba017977"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1777302711,"nonce":"vFnEG2/sts13yTfIVEyWu6BH93A=","message":"Fixed in commit 957c44b (review: fix stuck-snoozed split-brain when tracking ref update fails).\n\nRoot cause was in _wake_one() in src/b4/review_tui/_tracking_app.py: if save_tracking_ref() failed silently (returning False rather than raising), _restore_snoozed_tracking() returned the previous status anyway, and unsnooze_series() was called unconditionally. This left the DB with status='reviewing', snoozed_until=NULL while the tracking commit still said status='snoozed'.\n\nThe next rescan_branches() run that hit the slow path (any SHA mismatch) would then re-apply status='snoozed' from the tracking commit without restoring snoozed_until, producing a row that neither auto-wake query (get_expired_snoozed or get_tag_snoozed) could ever match — permanently stuck.\n\nThree-part fix:\n1. _restore_snoozed_tracking() now raises RuntimeError on save failure.\n2. _wake_one() returns early on exception, leaving the series fully snoozed rather than half-woken.\n3. rescan_branches() now calls snooze_series() (restoring snoozed_until) instead of update_series_status() when the tracking commit carries a snoozed status with a snoozed.until value.\n\nNote: the primary cause (git_revparse_tag only checks local refs, so a tag that exists upstream but hasn't been fetched never triggers a wake) is out of scope — b4 review does not run implicit git fetches on the user's behalf.","files":null}]}